#explore 2 variables
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = age, color=as.factor(age))) + geom_bar()

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = sex, color=as.factor(sex))) + geom_bar()

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = year, color=as.factor(year))) + geom_bar()

#explore 4 variables
ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = age, color=as.factor(age))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ degree)

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = age, color=as.factor(age))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ marital)

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = sex, color=as.factor(sex))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ degree)

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = sex, color=as.factor(sex))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ marital)

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = year, color=as.factor(year))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ degree)

ggplot(data = happy, aes(x = happy, fill = year, color=as.factor(year))) +
  geom_bar() + 
  facet_grid(. ~ marital)

From the data set, I can only interpret that the happiness levels vary if based on level of education or marital status. While there is a relatively larger number of data entries for high school or married, there appears to be a somewhat similar pattern of distribution among the different degree and marital status levels. While I believe I managed to convert the missing values to NA, tt does seem to show a small chunk of the data of people that didnt answer their happiness levels.
